data.content:
# .NET 8 Migration: BackgroundProcessor

## Key Breaking Changes

| .NET Framework | .NET 8 |
|---|---|
| `Thread.Abort()` | **Throws `PlatformNotSupportedException`** |
| `ThreadAbortException` | **Never raised** — dead code |
| `Thread.ResetAbort()` | **Removed entirely** |
| Manual `Thread` + `volatile bool` | Use `CancellationToken` + `Task` |

## Migrated Code

```csharp
public class BackgroundProcessor : IAsyncDisposable
{
    private Task? _workerTask;
    private CancellationTokenSource? _cts;

    public void Start()
    {
        _cts = new CancellationTokenSource();
        _workerTask = Task.Run(() => ProcessLoop(_cts.Token));
    }

    private async Task ProcessLoop(CancellationToken token)
    {
        while (!token.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            try
            {
                // Pass the token so blocking calls become cancellable
                var item = await GetNextItemAsync(token);
                await ProcessItemAsync(item, token);
            }
            catch (OperationCanceledException) when (token.IsCancellationRequested)
            {
                // Graceful shutdown requested — replaces ThreadAbortException
                RollbackCurrentTransaction();
                break; // exit loop cleanly; finally still runs
            }
            finally
            {
                FlushBuffers();
            }
        }
    }

    public async Task StopAsync(TimeSpan? timeout = null)
    {
        if (_cts is null || _workerTask is null)
            return;

        timeout ??= TimeSpan.FromSeconds(5);

        // Signal cancellation (replaces _running = false)
        await _cts.CancelAsync();

        // Wait with a hard deadline (replaces Thread.Sleep + Abort)
        if (_workerTask != await Task.WhenAny(_workerTask, Task.Delay(timeout.Value)))
        {
            // Worker didn't stop in time — log a warning.
            // There is NO equivalent to Thread.Abort(); you must
            // ensure all blocking calls respect the CancellationToken.
        }
    }

    public async ValueTask DisposeAsync()
    {
        await StopAsync();
        _cts?.Dispose();
    }
}
```

## Critical Pitfalls

**1. Blocking calls that ignore the token are un-cancellable.**
If `GetNextItem()` blocks on a synchronous API (legacy DB poll, `Monitor.Wait`, etc.), cancellation won't interrupt it. You **must** convert or wrap it:

```csharp
// Wrap a synchronous blocking call to respect cancellation
private async Task<Item> GetNextItemAsync(CancellationToken token)
{
    // Option A: API already supports cancellation
    return await _queue.DequeueAsync(token);

    // Option B: Wrap legacy blocking call (last resort — leaks a thread)
    return await Task.Run(() => GetNextItem(), token);
}
```

**2. `Thread.ResetAbort()` has no equivalent — and needs none.**
`OperationCanceledException` is a normal exception. It propagates normally through `finally` blocks without special handling.

**3. `volatile bool` is insufficient for async.**
`CancellationToken` is thread-safe, composable, and integrates with `async`/`await`. A `volatile bool` can't wake up a blocked `await`.

**4. Hosted services are preferred in ASP.NET / worker apps.**
If this runs in a host, inherit from `BackgroundService` instead:

```csharp
public class Processor : BackgroundService
{
    protected override async Task ExecuteAsync(CancellationToken stoppingToken)
    {
        while (!stoppingToken.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            var item = await GetNextItemAsync(stoppingToken);
            await ProcessItemAsync(item, stoppingToken);
        }
    }
}

// Registration:
builder.Services.AddHostedService<Processor>();
```

This gives you graceful shutdown, DI, and lifetime management for free.

**5. No force-kill exists in .NET 8.**
If a rogue task truly hangs, your only option is `Environment.Exit()` or an external process supervisor. Design all I/O to accept `CancellationToken` from the start.
